Setup

Packages, Data, Maps

Load the following packages and load the PM data from lectures 1 and 2. Select November 10th, 2018 and merge the data with the sites. Project using CA Albers projection shown in lecture 2.

library(ggplot2)
library(leaflet)
library(mapproj)
library(proj4)
library(geoR)
library(dplyr)
library(fields)

pm25 = read.csv("/Users/mf/Dropbox (University of Southern California)/Courses/PM569/Fall 2019/data/pm25_ca_2018.csv")
pm25.sites = read.csv("/Users/mf/Dropbox (University of Southern California)/Courses/PM569/Fall 2019/data/pm25_sites.csv")
pm_ca<-merge(pm25 %>% filter(date=="11/10/18"), pm25.sites, by='site_id')

proj_albers<-"+proj=aea +lat_1=34.0 +lat_2=40.5 +lon_0=-120.0 +x_0=0 +y_0=-4000000 +ellps=GRS80 +datum=NAD83 +units=km"

newcoords<-project(as.matrix(cbind(pm_ca$longitude, pm_ca$latitude)), proj=proj_albers)
pm_ca$x<-newcoords[,1]
pm_ca$y<-newcoords[,2]

Make a map of the PM2.5 concentrations

pm.pal = colorNumeric(c('darkgreen','goldenrod','brown','brown'),
                        domain=pm_ca$pm25)

  addProviderTiles('CartoDB.Positron') %>%

             opacity=1, fillOpacity=1, radius=500) %>%
  addLegend('bottomleft', pal=pm.pal, values=pm_ca$pm25,
            title='PM2.5 (ug/m3)', opacity=1)

We fit theoretical functions by OLS, WLS, Maximum Likelihood: - OLS fits to bins, but does not consider the correlation between bins - WLS fits to bins and does consider the correlation between bins - MLE fits to ALL data, not the bins

Remember, for the binned empirical semivariograms it is best to use the Cressie-Hawkins robust estimator. We can compare fits using SSE (for the bin fits) and AIC for the MLE fits.

# empirical semivariogram find distances
#cloud semivariogrm (ALL pairwise distances, a lot of points!)
vario1<-variog(lpm_geo_alb,option="cloud")
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
plot(vario1) 

# binned semivariogram with C-H robust
# max dist 200 km, use 12 bins
vario2<-variog(lpm_geo_alb,uvec=seq(0,200,l=12),option="bin", estimator.type="modulus")
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
plot(vario2,xlab="Distance (h), km")

# Eyeballed theoretical semivariogram (add curve to semivariogram plot)
curve(0.05+0.6*(1-exp(-x/120)),from = 0 , to=200, ylab="Semivariance", xlab="Distance (h)",add=T,col="red",lwd=1.5)

# fitting semivariogram by ols
# ini.cov.pars (sigma2,phi)
vfit_ols=variofit(vario2,ini.cov.pars=c(0.5,100),nugget=0.05,fix.nugget=FALSE,cov.model='exponential', weights="equal")
## variofit: covariance model used is exponential 
## variofit: weights used: equal 
## variofit: minimisation function used: optim
plot(vario2,xlab="Distance (h), km")
# add ols fitted line to the binned semivariogram and eyeballed curve
lines(vfit_ols,col="blue",lwd=1.5)

# summarizing the fit to get parameter estimates
summary(vfit_ols)

Kriging

For kriging, we are taking a fitted semivariogram, converting the function to a covariance (R dose it for us) and then interpolating the point referenced data to unobserved locations. - Can interpolate to other point locations - Can interpolate to a fine grid to get an interpolated surface

We need the fields() package to easily do image plots to check our results.

# kriging with likelihood fit
# create grid for kriging/interpolation

res=60
xs=seq(min(pm_ca$x),max(pm_ca$x),len=res)
ys=seq(min(pm_ca$y),max(pm_ca$y),len=res)
myGrid=expand.grid(xs,ys)
names(myGrid)=c('y','x')
# names of grid coordinates must match coordinate names in dataset that is being kriged

# kiriging with no trend (cte mean)
kriged_grid=krige.conv(lpm_geo_alb,locations=myGrid,krige=krige.control(obj.model=remlfit_gau), output=output.control(signal=TRUE))
## krige.conv: model with constant mean
## krige.conv: Kriging performed using global neighbourhood
# kiriging with linear trend
kriged_grid_trend=krige.conv(lpm_geo_alb,locations=myGrid,krige=krige.control(obj.model=remlfit_gau_trend,trend.d='1st',trend.l='1st'), output=output.control(signal=TRUE))
## krige.conv: model with mean given by a 1st order polynomial on the coordinates
## krige.conv: Kriging performed using global neighbourhood
#plot on grid
image.plot(xs,ys,matrix(kriged_grid$predict,res,res,byrow=FALSE),col=tim.colors(32))
map('state',add=TRUE)# project MAP!!!
points(pm_ca$x, pm_ca$y, pch=19,cex=0.4)

Kriging results on a nicer map

  • We need to transform the coordinates back to lat and lon
  • Also, since we logged the data we should exponentiate the predictions
proj_albers<-"+proj=aea +lat_1=34.0 +lat_2=40.5 +lon_0=-120.0 +x_0=0 +y_0=-4000000 +ellps=GRS80 +datum=NAD83 +units=km"
myGrid_ll<- project(myGrid, proj_albers, inverse=TRUE)


preds = data.frame(myGrid_ll, pred.pm=exp(kriged_grid$predict) %>% as.vector)
pred.pal = colorNumeric(c('darkgreen','gold1','brown'),
                             domain=preds$pred.pm)
preds %>% 
  leaflet() %>% 
  addProviderTiles("CartoDB.Positron") %>% 
  addCircles(lng=~x, lat=~y, color=~pred.pal(pred.pm),
             opacity=.7, fillOpacity=.7, radius=1e3) %>% # points w/ 1KM radius
  addLegend('bottomleft', pal=pred.pal, values=preds$pred.pm,
            title="Pred. PM2.5", opacity=.5)
